===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|shutten|lang=enm}}, {{term|shetten|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|scyttan||to cause rapid movement, shoot a bolt, shut, bolt, shut to, discharge a debt, pay off|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*skutjaną}}, {{m|gem-pro|*skuttjaną||to bar, bolt}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*skuttą}}, {{m|gem-pro|*skuttjō||bar, bolt, shed}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*(s)keud-||to drive, fall upon, rush}}. Cognate with {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|schutten||to shut in, lock up|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|schütten||to shut, lock in|lang=nds}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|schützen||to shut out, dam, protect, guard|lang=de}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|shuts|shutting|shut|shut}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[close]], to [[stop]] from being [[open]].
#: ''Please '''shut''' the door.''
#: ''The light was so bright I had to '''shut''' my eyes.''
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To [[close]], to [[stop]] being open.
#: ''If you wait too long, the automatic door will '''shut'''.''
# {{context|transitive|or|intransitive|chiefly|British|lang=en}} To [[close]] a [[business]] temporarily, or (of a business) to be closed.
#: ''The pharmacy is '''shut''' on Sunday.''
# To preclude; to exclude; to bar out.
#* Dryden
#*: '''shut''' from every shore

